reviews.review_text:
not bad for Lo-Fi ! Hey Gang,   of course,  this show has been widely circulated over the years as a top sounding soundboard.  However,  back in the day, beggars couldn't be choosers so this was probably passed around at first.  

I am curious of how the taper really pulled this one off... I mean the deck wasn't that small and back then some of the GD crew would look for "bootleggers" and cut their mic cables, take tapes and sometimes damage equipment.   It sounds like the mic isn't really that high above the crowd because of the occasional handclap or cheer which isn't that obtrusive.  Some of the greatest tapers and outstanding equipment can be ruined by excessive crowd cheer,  so sometimes FOB (front of board, or front of house mixing) isn't the best.  

You have to credit Sony for the one point microphone which is probably at 90 or 120 degrees (mid side or MS) which can yield a nice image without adverse phase issues.  Again, so many tapers did not understand this and some still don't understand it today.  This tape is actually clear,  vocals, jerry guitar,  bass still has a little punch, and you can still hear Bob's guitar.  The stereo field is rather narrow and the fidelity is low; I'm sure once this hit 2nd or 3rd generation it was over BUT that ain't the way it is nowadays !! 
Why this show has not been released commercially is beyond me; it has a certain vibe to it as the GD successfully  pulled of a large arena show back when it was really tough to do. 

So,  why not get a copy and try it on a boom box or portable wifi speaker for a camp fire sound... you can be surprised how neat it is to listen to music this way ... it works great for Lo Fi sources.
